{"key":"post-17889399","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>17889399</id>\n<content>Peat doesn't work at all as a substrate.&amp;nbsp; Coir is found in cities at pet stores.&amp;nbsp; Get it the blocks.&amp;nbsp; Avoid the coir from hydro stores as it usually has bacillus and trichoderma added since they're beneficial to plants.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Composted cow manure from a nursery or plant store works too, but mix it 50/50 with vermiculite to fluff it up and add minerals.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;If neighbors have horses, horse manure is the gold standard.&amp;nbsp; Collect field aged nuggets that have been out in the sun for at least a month or two.&amp;nbsp; As long as they're dry and the ammonia smell is gone, they're ready to pasteurize and use.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>17889461</next>\n<prev>17888689</prev>\n<first>17887850</first>\n<last>17889461</last>\n<when>1362200835</when>\n<utime>03/02/13 07:07 AM</utime>\n</post>"}